6 §1283. Context of public display
7 Public displays set forth in R.S. 25:1282(B), (C), (D), and (E) shall be
8 accompanied by a document entitled "Context for Acknowledging America's
9 Religious History as Culture, Tradition, and the History of Law" which shall read
10 as follows:
11 (1) Some documents stand out as pivotal in the religious history of America
12 and Louisiana's legal system, among which are the Mayflower Compact, The
13 Declaration of Independence as a legal foundation for the United States Constitution,
14 the Ten Commandments as one of the foundations of our legal system, and the
15 Northwest Ordinance, which was a primary document affirming faith and the first
16 congressional act legally prohibiting slavery. It is hoped that their study and relation
17 to each other and the history of our state and nation will foster an appreciation for
18 the role that religion has played in the culture, tradition, and legal history of the
19 law of America and the state of Louisiana and prompt further public study.
20 (2) American law, constitutionalism, and political theory have deep roots in
21 religion. American ideals about liberty, freedom, equality, legal responsibility and
22 codes of law, to mention a few, have roots and underpinnings in religion and biblical
23 literacy. The Ten Commandments, which are found in the Book of Exodus in the Old
24 Testament of the Bible, was were one of the earliest written expressions of law to be
25 incorporated in American legal systems. The Ten Commandments, or the law of
26 nature, also impacted the Declaration of Independence which refers to the "laws of
27 nature and of Nature's God."
